T1045.long: Software packing is a method of compressing or encrypting an executable. Packing an executable changes the file signature in an attempt to avoid signature-based detection. Most decompression techniques decompress the executable code in memory.

strings: !This program cannot be run in DOS mode.
-o FILE  --output=FILE  Operate interactively, sending output to FILE.
-i  --ignore-case  Consider upper- and lower-case to be the same.
-b  --ignore-space-change  Ignore changes in the amount of white space.
-B  --ignore-blank-lines  Ignore changes whose lines are all blank.
-I RE  --ignore-matching-lines=RE  Ignore changes whose lines all match RE.
-w NUM  --width=NUM  Output at most NUM (default 130) characters per line.
-l  --left-column  Output only the left column of common lines.
-t  --expand-tabs  Expand tabs to spaces in output.
-d  --minimal  Try hard to find a smaller set of changes.
-H  --speed-large-files  Assume large files and many scattered small changes.
If FILE1 or FILE2 is `-', read standard input.
both files to be compared are directories
edit then use the left version
edit then use the right version
edit then use the left and right versions concatenated
